# ddc-mode-switcher configuration
#
# This file is sourced as a bash script. Uncomment and edit the settings below
# to match your monitor setup.
#
# Location: ~/.config/ddc-mode-switcher/config
#
# How to find your values:
#   ddcutil detect        → I2C bus number
#   ddcutil capabilities  → VCP codes for your monitor's mode switch
#   gdctl show            → connector names, current modes, scales (GNOME only)
#
# For more information see: https://github.com/Gunther-Schulz/display-mode-switcher

# =============================================================================
# Required settings
# =============================================================================

# I2C bus number for the monitor.
# Find it with: ddcutil detect
#BUS=5

# Primary monitor connector name as reported by gdctl.
# Find it with: gdctl show
#CONN=DP-2

# Desktop (native) resolution — the mode to restore to after gaming.
# Must match exactly what gdctl reports (resolution only, no refresh rate).
# Example: for a 5K monitor that switches to 2K gaming mode, this is "5120x2880".
#NATIVE_RES=5120x2880

# DDC toggle sequence: array of "VCP_CODE VALUE" pairs sent in order.
# Each entry becomes a separate "ddcutil setvcp" call.
#
# Example for ASUS ROG Strix XG27JCG (Frame Rate Boost):
#   VCP 0x03 value 1 = open OSD menu, value 20 = confirm toggle
#TOGGLE_STEPS=("0x03 1" "0x03 20")

# =============================================================================
# Optional settings
# =============================================================================

# Secondary monitor connector for multi-monitor gdctl restore.
# Only needed if you have a second monitor whose layout should be restored.
#SECONDARY_CONN=DP-3

# Fallback scale values used when gdctl can't read the current scale.
# These are applied during restore if the scale couldn't be captured.
#DEFAULT_SCALE=1.0
#DEFAULT_SECONDARY_SCALE=1.0

# Max seconds to poll gdctl for mode switch confirmation (default: 10).
# The script polls once per second until the mode changes or this timeout
# is reached. In practice, switches usually confirm within 1-3 seconds.
#SWITCH_TIMEOUT=10

# Blind wait in seconds when gdctl is unavailable (default: 2).
# Used on non-GNOME compositors where mode verification isn't possible.
#FALLBACK_WAIT=2
